<DOC><DOCNO> AP880602-0302 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1315EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-Britain-InterestRates     06-02 0177</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Britain-Interest Rates,0183</SECOND><HEAD>British Banks Raise Base Rate to 8 Percent</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Britain's major commercial banks, heeding a signalfrom the Bank of England, announced they would raise their baselending rate by half a percentage point to 8 percent.   Barclays Bank PLC, Midland Bank PLC, National Westminster BankPLC and Lloyds Bank PLC said Thursday they would increase thebenchmark rate, effective Friday.   The Bank of England, apparently responding to the slumpingBritish pound, sent its signal at noon local time by announcing itwould raise a key money-market intervention rate.   The pound has fallen sharply against the dollar and the WestGerman mark in the last few days as the market's attention hasshifted away from sterling into the dollar and other majorcurrencies.   The British base rate was last changed on May 17, when it wascut to 7.5 percent from 8 percent as British authorities attemptedto estrain a strong rise in the pound.   Corporate borrowers can obtain loans from commercial banks atone percentage point above the base rate.</TEXT></DOC>